erranean, The Shamama Case offers a riveting history of citizenship across regional, cultural, and political borders.On its face, the crux of the lawsuit seemed simple: To which state did Shamama belong when he died? But the case produced hundreds of pages in legal briefs and thousands of dollars in lawyers’ fees before the man's estate could be distributed among his quarrelsome heirs. Jessica Marglin follows the unfolding of events, from Shamama's rise to power in Tunis and his self-imposed exile in France, to his untimely death in Livorno and the clashing visions of nationality advanced during the lawsuit. Marglin brings to life a Dickensian array of individuals involved in the case: family members who hoped to inherit the estate; Tunisian government officials; an Algerian Jewish fixer; rabbis in Palestine, Tunisia, and Livorno; and some of Italy’s most famous legal minds.Drawing from a wealth of correspondence, legal briefs, rabbinic opinions, and court rulings, The Shamama Case reimagines how we think about Jews, the Mediterranean, and belonging in the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConflict of lawsxInheritance and successionzItalyxCases. 0aJewsxLegal status, laws, etc.zItalyxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewsxLegal status, laws, etc.zTunisiaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh  aAir mass.  aAnnoyance.  aApprobation.  aArmenian Question.  aAshanti Empire.  aAward.  aBeatific vision.  aBranch (banking).  aBrand.  aBrazilians.  aCannes.  aCapitalism.  aCensure.  aCitizenship.  aCommon good.  aConceptualization (information science).  aConsumer.  aContract A.  aDeclaration of war.  aDecree.  aDefeat and dissolution of the Ottoman Empire.  aDemonization.  aDon Patinkin.  aDuce.  aDuress.  aEmblem.  aEthics.  aF